":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Burslem (Staffs), recorded as  <i>Burwardeslime</i> in 1252 and  <i>Burseleym</i> in 1485."],"variants":[{"name":"Boslem","meanings":["English, Scottish: variant of   Burslem  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":67,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Burslem was born about 1482, in Burslem, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Thomas de Burslem, was 33 and his mother, Lydia, was 28. He married Joan Rowley about 1507, in Burslem, Staffordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1555, in Burslem, Staffordshire, England, at the age of 74."},"et":{"Abt 1482–1555":"umbes 1482–1555","1482–1555":"1482–1555","1490–1594":"1490–1594","1509–1562":"1509–1562","1511–1596":"1511–1596","1530–Ma